\begin_layout Title
On the Beta Transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
December 2017 (Updated Feb 2018 and Dec 2018)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
linasvepstas@gmail.com
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The beta transformation is the iterated map 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta x\,\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 The special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 is known as the Bernoulli map, and is exactly solvable.
 The Bernoulli map provides a model for pure, unrestrained chaotic (ergodic)
 behavior: it is the full invariant shift on the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The Cantor space consists of infinite strings of binary digits; it is notable
 for many properties, including that it can represent the real number line.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The beta transformation defines a subshift: iterated on the unit interval,
 it singles out a subspace of the Cantor space that is invariant under the
 action of the left-shift operator.
 That is, lopping off one bit at a time gives back the same subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text reviews assorted general properties, and then focuses primarily
 on the transfer operator (the Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron operator) and it's
 spectrum.
 Discrete eigenvalues seem to lie on a circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

 in the complex plane.
 Given that the transfer operator is purely real, the appearance of such
 a quasi-unitary spectrum unexpected.
 The spectrum appears to be the limit of a dense set of quasi-cyclotomic
 polynomials, the positive real roots of which include the Golden and silver
 ratios, the Pisot numbers, the n-bonacci (tribonacci, tetranacci, 
\emph on
etc.
\emph default
) numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This text does not assume much mathematical sophistication on the part of
 the reader, and should be approachable by those with minimal or no prior
 experience in ergodic theory.
 Most of the development is casual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta transformation is the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{\beta}(x)=\beta x\mod1
\]

\end_inset

iterated on the real unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 taken to be a real positive constant.
 For the special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

, this is the Bernoulli process, the ergodic process of random coin flips.
 This case is solvable, in that it is very well-explored, as a canonical
 model of ergodic behavior.
 The beta transformation is less-well studied; a full review of results
 is presented after this introduction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The periodic orbits of the beta transform can be characterized by quasi-cyclotom
ic polynomials; these are polynomials of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-b_{0}z^{k}-b_{1}z^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k-1}z-1$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 being binary bits (zero or one).
 However, as always, the periodic orbits are a set of measure zero, and
 a fuller picture is obtained by studying the action of the map on distributions
 on the unit interval.
 Informally, this is given by the pushforward of the beta transform, acting
 on a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho\right]\left(x\right)=\sum_{y\in t^{-1}\left(x\right)}\frac{\rho\left(y\right)}{\left|df/dx\right|_{y}}
\]

\end_inset

where the denominator is understood as the Jacobian determinant.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator, acting on some space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Different spaces result in different properties for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

; commonly explored are the polynomials, and the square-integrable functions,
 although in certain special cases, the analysis can be extended to highly
 singular, continuous-nowhere functions.
 The pushforward operator is generically called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ruelle–Frobenius–Perron operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The largest eigenvalue is conventionally called the Frobenius–Perron eigenvalue;
 it is usually equal to one.
 Solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\mu=\mu$
\end_inset

 define an invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on the unit interval.
 It is invariant in the usual sense of dynamical systems: one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu\circ t_{\beta}^{-1}\right)\left(x\right)=\mu\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The proper formal statement of this is to invoke the sigma-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 of Borel sets on the unit interval.
 The inverse of the beta transform is then a map 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}^{-1}:\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 while the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a sigma-additive measure.
 The pushforward nature of the transfer operator is now more readily visible:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho=\rho\circ t_{\beta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and one is interested in the eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L_{\beta}\rho=\lambda\rho}$
\end_inset

 of this operator, where the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 is restricted in various ways, 
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 by limiting it to functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that can be interpreted as being polynomials, or square-integrable, 
\emph on
etc.

\emph default
 on the unit interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remainder of this section provides a very basic review of some elementary
 properties of the beta transform, starting with the full shift, aka the
 Bernoulli shift.
 The section is completed with a survey of other research results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bernoulli shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift (
\emph on
aka
\emph default
 the bit-shift map, the dyadic transform or the full shift) is an iterated
 map on the unit interval, given by iteration of the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b(x)=\begin{cases}
2x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
2x-1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:Bernoulli shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The symbolic dynamics of this map gives the binary digit expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{n}(x)=(b\circ b\circ\cdots\circ b)(x)=b(b(\cdots b(x)\cdots))
\]

\end_inset

to denote the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold iteration of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{0}(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 The symbolic dynamics is given by the bit-sequence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le b^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le b^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:bernoulli-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(Attention: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a subscript on the left, and a superscript on the right! The left is
 a sequence, the right is an iteration.
 Using the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 one both sides is a convenient abuse of notation.) Of course, the symbolic
 dynamics recreates the initial real number:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}b_{n}\left(x\right)2^{-n-1}\label{eq:homomorphism}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

All of this is just a fancy way of saying that a real number can be written
 in terms of it's base-2 binary expansion.
 That is, the binary digits for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=b_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli shift has many interesting properties, connecting it to the
 Cantor set and a large class of self-similar fractals.
 It is also connected to the modular group and elliptic functions (thence
 to number theory).
 It is also the primary example of an ergodic system, and, in a sense, has
 far-reaching implications for ergodic systems via Ornstein theory.
 These various connections are far too numerous to review here, beyond these
 breif mentions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current task is to attempt to see how many of these properties still
 hold in the more general case of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shift space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shift space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is formally defined to be a set of infinite sequences of a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 letters (or symbols), together with a shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 that takes each sequence, and lops off the left-most symbol.
 For the Bernoulli shift, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 letters, taken from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For the Bernoulli shift, one is typically interested in the set of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 possible infinite sequences: this is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 One writes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 for this shift space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 denoting countable infinity.
 For the Bernoulli shift, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the shift operator: it just lops of the left-most symbol.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, a shift space does not have to include every possible sequence
 of symbols; it does, however, by definition, have to be shift-invariant.
 That is, given some set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of infinite sequences of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 symbols, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a shift space if and only if, by loping off the leading symbol of each
 string, one regains 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 again.
 That is, a shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 must obey 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TS=S
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left\{ 000\cdots,111\cdots\right\} $
\end_inset

 contains only two elements: the string of all zeros, and the string of
 all ones; loping off the leading digit just returns 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 again.
 In general, shift spaces may contain a finite, or a countable, or an uncountabl
e number of elements.
 In general, one defines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the space 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 of all possible strings of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 symbols.
 Subsets that are shift spaces are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

subshifts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symbolic dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 also deserve some mention: given one specific sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 out of the shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, one can ponder 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

where it goes to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as one lops off a symbol at a time.
 This gives the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

symbolic dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the sequence.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

orbit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is defined as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ T^{m}x\,|\,\mbox{integer }m\ge0\right\} $
\end_inset

 – that is, the set of all places that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 goes to.
 There are several possibilities: one is that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a fixed point, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $Tx=x$
\end_inset

.
 Another is that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a repeating sequence of symbols, in which case iteration repeats as
 well: 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}x=x$
\end_inset

 holds whenever the repeat length is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

; this is a periodic orbit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most importantly, when there are non-periodic orbits, then there are uncountaly
 many of them.
 That is, the number of periodic orbits is always countable: ther are at
 most 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 starting points for an orbit, and they are of at most length 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 This includes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eventually periodic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 orbits: those that begin with some finite intial sequence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 moves, eventually settling into a periodic recurrance.
 This cannot be done for the non-periodic orbits: they cannot be placed
 in lexicographic order; as the Cantor slash argument applies.
 The non-periodic orbits are always uncountable.
 In this sense, the non-periodic orbits are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more important
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that the make up the bulk of all orbits.
 There are situations in which the periodic orbits can be said to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

govern
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the dynamics of the aperiodic ones; this is termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent structure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However such concepts are advanced, and are not obviously applicable to
 the current situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, the text will in general confine itself to the uncountable
 case.
 Periodic orbits exist, but will be ignored; in a certain strict sense,
 they constitute a set of measure zero.
 A number of glosses like this will be made: for example, the real numbers,
 and the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 are both uncountable; however, they are not in one-to-one correspondence,
 as some real numbers can have two different representations as bit sequences.
 Specifically, these are the dyadic fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2n+1\right)/2^{m}$
\end_inset

 for positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 – they can be validly represented by bit-sequences ending in all-zeros,
 or all-ones.
 There are only countably many such fractions; for the most part, this distincti
on between the real number line, and the Cantor space will be ignored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beta shift
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta shift is similar to the Bernoulli shift, replacing the number 2
 by a constant real-number value 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

.
 It can be defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}(x)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:downshift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map, together with similar maps, is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Iterated-piece-wise-linear"

\end_inset

 below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as the Bernoulli shift generates a sequence of digits, so does the
 beta shift: write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{n}=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:down-bits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Given the symbolic dynamics, one can reconstruct the original value whenever
 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{k_{0}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Written this way, the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}(x)$
\end_inset

 clearly acts as a shift on this sequence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}(x)=\frac{k_{1}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{2}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{3}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{k_{4}}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\cdots\right)\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

In this sense, this shift is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exactly solvable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: the above provides a closed-form solution for iterating and un-iterating
 the sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multiplying out the above sequence, one obtains the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, namely the series
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{k_{n}}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:shift series}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the bit-sequence that was extracted by iteration can be used to
 reconstruct the original real number.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bernoulli-bits"

\end_inset

 gives the Bernoulli shift: 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}\left(x\right)=b\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the Bernoulli shift, not every possible bit-sequence occurs in this
 system.
 It is a subshift of the full shift: it is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 This is explored in greater detail in a later section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Associated polynomial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The iterated shift can also be written as a finite sum.
 This is noted here; it will be useful in later sections.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}(x)=\beta\left(x-\frac{k_{0}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{2}(x)=\beta^{2}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\left(\beta k_{0}+k_{1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{3}(x)=\beta^{3}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\left(\beta^{2}k_{0}+\beta k_{1}+k_{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The general form is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta}^{p}(x)=\beta^{p}x-\frac{\beta}{2}\sum_{m=0}^{p-1}k_{m}\beta^{p-m-1}\label{eq:iterated shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m}$
\end_inset

 depend on both 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and are piece-wise discontinuous functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, this is not a true polynomial; however, this polynomial-like representation
 will be useful, later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density Visualizations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long-term dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift can be visualized by means of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bifurcation diagram
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Scare quotes are used, as these are imprecise terms; greater precision
 will be provided shortly.
 The idea of a bifurcation diagram was made famous by the Feigenbaum map
 (shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Logistic-Map-Bifurcation"

\end_inset

), and so the same idea is applied here: track orbits over long periods
 of time, and see where they go.
 This forms a density, which can be numerically explored by historgramming.
 This is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Undershift-Bifurcation-Diagram"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When this is done for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift, one thing becomes immediately apparent: there are no actual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bifurcations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, no period-doubling regions, none of the stuff normally associated with
 the Feigenbaum map.
 Although there are periodic orbits, these form a set of measure zero: the
 iteration produces purely chaotic motion for almost all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>1$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense, the beta transform provides a clean form of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure chaos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
