\begin_layout Standard
A brief review of dynamical systems is in order, as it provides a coherent
 language with which to talk about and think about the beta-shift.
 Understanding this avoids the need for weasel-words and imprecise hand-waving
 when making claims and statements; common phrases can be given a precise
 meaning.
 This section reviews textbook-standard material; it is included here only
 to allow this text to be self-contained.
 Later parts of this text will appeal to ideas presented here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 can be given a topology, the product topology.
 The open sets of this topology are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cylinder sets
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These are strings in three symbols: a finite number of 0 and 1 symbols,
 and an infinite number of * symbols, the latter meaning 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

don't care
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Set union is defined location-by-location, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\cup*=1\cup*=*$
\end_inset

 and set intersection as 
\begin_inset Formula $0\cap*=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cap*=1$
\end_inset

.
 Set complement exchanges 0 and 1 and leaves * alone: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{0}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{1}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{*}=*$
\end_inset

.
 The topology is then the collection of all cylinder sets.
 Note that the intersection of any finite number of cylinder sets is still
 a cylinder set, as is the union of an infinite number of them.
 The product topology does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 contain any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

points
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: strings consisting solely of just 0 and 1 are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 allowed in the topology.
 By definition, topologies only allow finite intersections, and thus don't
 provide any way of constructing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

points
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Of course, points can always be added 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

by hand
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but doing so tends to generate a topology that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

too fine
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; in particular, the common-sense notions of a continuous function are ruined
 by fine topologies.
 The product topology is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coarse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Borel algebra, or sigma-algebra, takes the topology and also allows
 set complement.
 This effectively changes nothing, as the open sets are still the cylinder
 sets, although now they are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

clopen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as they are both closed and open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the Borel algebra by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 A shift is now a map 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 that lops off the leading symbol of a given cylinder set (XXX FIXME lop
 off only for full shift!).
 This is provides the strong theoretical advantages over working with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point dynamics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: confusions about counting points and orbits and defining densities go
 away.
 This is done by recasting discussion in terms of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 from Borel sets to the reals (or the complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 or other fields, when this is interesting).
 An important class of such functions are the measures.
 These are functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 that are positive, and are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compatible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with the sigma algebra, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(A\cup B\right)=\mu\left(A\right)+\mu\left(B\right)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\varnothing$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(A\cap B\right)=\mu\left(A\right)\mu\left(B\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 For the total space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 (here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the Cantor space), one case 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\Omega\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prototypical example of a measure is the Bernoulli measure, which assigns
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to any string containing a single 0 and the rest all *'s.
 By complement, a string containing a single 1 and the rest all *'s has
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

.
 The rest follows from the sigma algebra: a cylinder set consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 zeros and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 ones has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{m}\left(1-p\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It is usually convenient to take 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fair coin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; the Bernoulli process is a sequence of coin tosses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The map given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a homomorphism from the Cantor space to the unit interval.
 It extends naturally to a map from the Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 to the algebra of intervals on the unit interval.
 It is not an isomorphism: cylinder sets are both open and closed, whereas
 intervals on the real number line are either open, or closed (or half-open).
 It is convenient to take the map as a map to closed intervals, so that
 it's a surjection onto the reals, although usually, this detail does not
 matter.
 What does matter is of one takes 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

, then the Bernoulli measure is preserved: it is mapped onto the conventional
 measure on the real-number line.
 Thus, the cylinder set 
\begin_inset Formula $0***\cdots$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1/2\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1***\cdots$
\end_inset

 is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1/2,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and both have a measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 and this extends likewise to all intersections and unions.
 Points have a measure of zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the map of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is not an isomorphism, it is more-or-less safe form most practical purposes
 to treat it as such.
 For any closed interval, there is a unique corresponding cylinder set.
 The only trouble arises at points: all dyadic rationals have two expansions
 not one, and so there, the map is not invertable.
 However, the points all have a measure of zero in both cases, and there
 are only a countable number of such points, and the mapping always takes
 points to points.
 Thus, the inverse exists for almost all members of the algebra and is unique
 whenever an interval has positive measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much of what is said above still holds for subshifts.
 Recall, a subshift 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subset\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the shift 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $TS=S$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 inherits a topology from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, this is the subspace topology.
 The Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is similarly defined, as are measures.
 One can now (finally!) give a precise definition for an invariant measure:
 it is a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\circ T^{-1}=\mu$
\end_inset

, or more precisely, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(T^{-1}\left(\sigma\right)\right)=\mu\left(\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 for almost all cylinder sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 This is what shift invariance looks like.
 Note carefully that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and not 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is used in the definition.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a surjection while 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is not: every cylinder set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 in the subshift 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

came from somewhere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; we want to define invariance for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and not just for some of them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is technically called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pushforward
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and it defines a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 on the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 It is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F\to\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:f\mapsto f\circ T^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 It is obviously linear, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(af+bg\right)=a\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(f\right)+b\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(g\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This pushforward is canonically called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transfer operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Like any linear operator, it has a spectrum.
 The precise spectrum depends on the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical example is again the Bernoulli shift.
 For this, we invoke the inverse of the mapping of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a function defined on the unit interval, instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is the space of real-analytic functions on the unit interval, that is,
 the space all power series in 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, then the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is discrete.
 It consists of the Bernoulli polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and have a corresponding eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}B_{n}=2^{-n}B_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 is the invariant measure on the full shift.
 For the space of square-integrable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 is continuous, and consists of the unit disk in the complex plane; the
 corresponding eigenfunctions are fractal.
 Even more interesting constructions are possible; the Minkowski question
 mark function provides an example of a measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is invariant under the shift defined by the Gauss map 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)\mapsto\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

.
 That is, as a measure, it solves 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}?^{\prime}=?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $?$
\end_inset

 the Minkowski question mark function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 it's derivative; note that the derivative is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

continuous nowhere
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This rather confusing idea can be completely dispelled by observing that
 it is well-defined on all cylinder sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 and is finite on all of them – not only finite, but less than one, as any
 good measure must obey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These last examples are mentioned so as to reinforce the idea working with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 instead of the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 really does offer some strong conceptual advantages.
 They also reinforce the idea that the Bernoulli shift is not the only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (besides the question-mark function, there is also the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odometer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In the following text, we will be working with subshifts, primarily the
 beta-shift, but will draw on ideas from the above so as to make rigorous
 statements about measureability and invariance, without having to descend
 into either 
\emph on
ad hoc
\emph default
 hand-waving or provide painfully difficult (and confusing) reasoning about
 subsets of the real-number line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beta Transformation Literature Review and References
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation, in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

 has been well-studied over the decades.
 The beta-expansion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"

\end_inset

 was introduced by A.
 Renyi
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Renyi57"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who demonstrates the existence of the invariant measure.
 The ergodic properties of the transform were proven by W.
 Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who also shows that the system is weakly mixing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression for the invariant measure was independently obtained
 by A.O.
 Gel'fond
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gelfond59"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and by W.
 Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{\beta}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\varepsilon_{n}\left(y\right)}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:invariant measure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{n}\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }t_{\beta}^{n}\left(1\right)\le y\\
1 & \mbox{ otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a normalization constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the way in which a dyadic rational 
\begin_inset Formula $p/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 has two different binary expansions, one ending in all-zeros, and a second
 ending in all-ones, so one may also ask if and when a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 might have more than one 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion (for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

).
 In general, it can; N.
 Sidorov shows that almost every number has a continuum of such expansions!
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sidorov03"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 This signals that the beta shift behaves rather differently from the Cantor
 set in it's embedding.
 This is explored in greater detail in a subsequent section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

univoke numbers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are those values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for which there is only one, unique expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 These are studied by De Vries.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeVries06"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation has been shown to have the same ergodicity properties as
 the Bernoulli shift.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dajani97"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The fact that the beta shift, and its subshifts are all ergodic is established
 by Climenhaga and Thompson.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Clim10"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative to the notion of ergodicity is the notion of universality:
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion is universal if, for any given finite string of bits, that finite
 string occurs somewhere in the expansion.
 This variant of universality was introduced by Erdös and Komornik
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Erdos98"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Its is shown by N.
 Sidorov that almost every 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion is universal.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sidorov02"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Conversely, there are some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for which rational numbers have purely periodic 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansions;
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczewski10"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 all such numbers are Pisot numbers.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schmidt80"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbolic dynamics of the beta-transformation was analyzed by F.
 Blanchard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blanchard89"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A characterization of the periodic points are given by Bruno Maia
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maia07"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A discussion of various open problems with respect to the beta expansion
 is given by Akiyama.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Akiyama09"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the beta expansion is expanded to the entire real-number line, one
 effectively has a representation of reals in a non-integer base.
 One may ask about arithmetic properties, such as the behavior of addition
 and multiplication, in this base - for example, the sum or product of two
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-integers may have a fractional part! Bounds on the lengths of these fractional
 parts, and related topics, are explored by multiple authors.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Guimond01,Julien06,Hbaib13"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certain values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 - generally, the Pisot numbers, generate fractal tilings,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thurston89,Berthe05,Ito05,Adamczewski10,Akiyama09"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 which are generalizations of the Rauzy fractal.
 An overview, with common terminology and definitions is provided by Akiyama.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Akiyama17"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The tilings, sometimes called (generalized) Rauzy fractals, an be thought
 of as living in a direct product of Euclidean and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic spaces.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berthe04"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of finite beta-expansions constitutes a language, in the formal
 sense of model theory and computer science.
 This language is recursive (that is, decidable by a Turing machine), if
 and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a computable real number.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Simonsen11"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The zeta function, and a lap-counting function, are given by Lagarias
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lagarias94"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The Hausdorff dimension, the topological entropy and general notions of
 topological pressure arising from conditional variational principles is
 given by Daniel Thompson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thompson10"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A proper background on this topic is given by Barreira and Saussol
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barreira01"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of the topics or results cited above are made use of, or further expanded
 on, or even touched on in the following.
 This is not intentional, but rather a by-product of different goals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Symbolic Dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The baseline for for all subsequent comparisons will be the Bernoulli shift
 and the Cantor set.
 It is worthwhile to review assorted basic facts about these.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The space of all possible sequences of binary digits is termed the Cantor
 set.
 It is the Cartesian product of infinitely many copies of the set containing
 two elements:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\left\{ 0,1\right\} \times\cdots=\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}=2^{\omega}
\]

\end_inset

This space has a natural topology, the product topology, which differs sharply
 from the natural topology on the real-number line.
 Essentially all of the strange phenomena of fractals and of iterated functions
 follows from the product topology on this sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Symbolic Dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that iteration can generate strings of binary digits, and that these
 can be reassembled back into real numbers, it is interesting to ask what
 those mappings look like.
 To firm up the notation, let 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left(b_{n}\right)=\left(b_{0},b_{1,},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 denote a sequence of bits (or symbols) and write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{\beta}\left(B\right)=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:beta-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as the real number generated from that sequence.
 Conversely, given a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\left(k_{n;\beta}\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 denote the sequence of bits obtained by iterating the beta shift on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

; that is, the sequence generated by eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"

\end_inset

.
 The bit sequence for 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is just the bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b_{n}\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 generated by eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bernoulli-bits"

\end_inset

.
 The transformations between symbol sequences and real numbers make sense
 only when 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two interesting functions can be considered.
 One is the compressor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}(y)=x_{2}\left(K_{\beta}\left(y\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the other is the expander
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}(y)=x_{\beta}\left(K_{2}\left(y\right)\right)\label{eq:expander function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compressor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expander
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are being invented here to indicate negative and positive Lyapunov exponents
 associated with the two functions.
 For almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, the compressor function is pushing nearby points closer together; the
