\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bergman Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a matrix operator in Hessenberg form, it can be interpreted as a right-shi
ft on the space of polynomials.
 That is, given an unreduced Hessenberg matrix with matrix entries 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}$
\end_inset

, one can write a recurrence relation that defines a sequence of polynomials
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
zp_{n}\left(z\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{n+1}A_{kn}p_{k}\left(z\right)\label{eq:Hessenberg polynomials}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\left(z\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This relation is easily solvable in closed form, as the recurrence relation
 terminates in a finite number of steps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important property of these polynomials is that the zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 correspond to the eigenvalues of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 principle submatrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Numeric exploration of these polynomials confirms the previous results
 on eigenvalues obtained from direct diagonalization: the zeros of the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 seems to lie mostly near the circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

, distributed uniformly over all angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all of the sub-diagonal entries obey 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n+1,n}>0$
\end_inset

, then the polynomials form an orthonormal basis for Bergman space.
 That is, there exists a domain in the complex plane on which the polynomials
 provide a basis for a Hilbert space of holomorphic functions on that domain
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saff12,Tomeo11,Escri11"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 That is, one has the orthogonality relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{mn}=\int_{D}p_{m}\left(\overline{z}\right)p_{n}\left(z\right)d\mu\left(z\right)
\]

\end_inset

for some domain 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 of the complex plane, and some (Borel) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu$
\end_inset

 on that domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as an operator with a continuous spectrum.
 To do this, fix a certain, specific value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z=c$
\end_inset

 a constant, and then notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=\left(p_{n}\left(z\right)\right)_{n=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is a vector having the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}\vec{p}=z\vec{p}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 is a left-eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

; equivalently, a right-eigenvector of its transpose 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, the spectrum is continuous on the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can also be interpreted as a right-shift on Bergman space.
 To do this, define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}\left(w,z\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p_{k}\left(w\right)A_{kn}p_{n}\left(\overline{z}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then, given some holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 decomposed in terms of the polynomials, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)=\sum_{n}a_{n}p_{n}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

, one has that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{A}f\right]\left(w\right)= & \int\mathcal{A}\left(w,z\right)f\left(z\right)d\mu\left(z\right)\\
= & \sum_{k}\sum_{n}p_{k}\left(w\right)A_{kn}a_{n}\\
= & w\sum_{n}a_{n}p_{n}\left(w\right)\\
= & wf\left(w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

That is, given a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{0},a_{1},a_{2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

, the Hessenberg matrix acts as a right-shift, mapping it to the sequence
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,a_{0},a_{1},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is perhaps a bit silly, as one could instead just perform the same
 manipulation without the 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

, by observing that, formally,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}\left(w,z\right)=w\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p_{k}\left(w\right)p_{n}\left(\overline{z}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above treatment is breezy and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

formal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, paying no heed to summability, convergence or responding to any questions
 about what spaces the various vectors may live in.
 This is as appropriate, since the task here is to discover which spaces
 are the appropriate ones, when the Hessenberg matrix arises from the beta
 shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a bit mis-used, here, as a vague synonym for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinite-dimensional matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Properly, the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be reserved for an infinite-dimensional matrix acting on some given
 space, having general properties that are independent of the basis chosen
 for that space.
 So far, that might not be the case here: the infinite-dimensional matrices
 here might not be bounded operators; they might not even be continuous,
 viz.
 we have not ruled out the possibility that the space of interest is some
 Fréchet space or some more general topological vector space.
 It is well known that operators on such spaces can have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unexpected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 discontinuities, unexpected in that they are not seen in ordinary Banach
 spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At any rate, if polynomials obtained from the beta shift are orthogonal
 on some domain 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 that is the support of some measure 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu$
\end_inset

, it is not at all clear what this measure might be.
 They are certainly not orthogonal on the unit disk, with uniform measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice also that the above treatment seems to be a special case of a more
 general principle: when an operator has a continuous spectrum, it can sometimes
 be interpreted as a right-shift.
 That is, given some arbitrary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, then if one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}f=\lambda f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 takes arbitrary values 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in D\subset\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 can be taken to be a right-shift operator, provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f\left(\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed into a set of orthogonal polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

